data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous LINQ via an explicit **sync-over-async opt-in** (e.g., `CosmosOptionsExtension` or `EnableSyncOverAsync()`). In .NET 11, **that opt-in is removed entirely**. The Cosmos DB provider now only supports async operations.

Every synchronous call in your repository — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime.

## How to fix it

Convert all sync methods to their async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
2. Methods marked `async`, renamed with `Async` suffix
3. `ToList()` → `await ToListAsync()`
4. `First()` → `await FirstAsync()`
5. `Count()` → `await CountAsync()`
6. `SaveChanges()` → `await SaveChangesAsync()`

The async LINQ methods come from `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` (ensure `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;` is present). You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through your callers (controllers, services, etc.).
